Forcing university students and school children to do sports is not a violation of their freedom to choose the life they wish.
The life style our young people conduct freaks me out and taking action is a must for their own good.
Doing sports does not boil down to whether they want to do or not, it is a prerequisite to establish a healthy society.
Three ideas are to discuss in this piece of paper.
Doing sports must be obligatory in any curriculum, the benefits of doing sports are undeniable, and students must not be left for their own devices.
To begin with, any successful curriculum must include sports.
Sports at our universities and schools are not just for embellishment but an integrated component in education.
However, forcing students to do sports does not imply to force them violently.
Some tricks to adopt, for instance, can be in a form of initiatives like giving our students the freedom to choose the type of sport they fancy.
Also important is the idea of competition.
Students can be lured by rewarding competitions.
As to the benefits of doing sports, they are too many to count in this piece of paper.
First, doing sports are a good shield against addiction to alcohol or smoking opium.
Second, doing sports results in having a healthy society.
A healthy society is an active and productive one.
Third, research shows that students who do sports regularly have a positive view about life and high spirit.
This is of vital importance for their school performance.
Nevertheless, forcing university students and school students to do sport is not the end; it is the beginning.
Universities and schools should accommodate students with decent and healthy food, clean cloakroom gym and so on and so forth.
Knowing the financial background of our students is a must too.
In fine, forcing students to do sport is for their own good after all.
Students' current lifestyle is detrimental and poisonous and forcing them to do sports implicitly is our duty.
