There has always been a lot of heated debate surrounding the issue of zoos.
Even nowadays opinions are divided as to whether zoos should be definitely banned or these parks should continue to play a key role in conservation efforts.
While it is true that animal wellbeing may be at risk if natural habitats are not properly recreated, I think the advantages of zoos as conservation temples, research incubators and learning fields are very well-documented.
First of all, zoos play a pivotal role in protecting endangered species and saving animals from extinction.
As far as animals\u2019 health is involved, there is no denying that these places are key to survival of wild species which are increasingly threatened by poachers, other wild predators, as well as shrinking natural habitat as a consequence of climate change.
Next, another crucial aim of zoos is to foster research projects so as to broaden the knowledge on animal behaviours and illnesses, thus increasing their physical and mental wellbeing.
There are teams of international scientists that are devoted specifically to carry out first-rate research which is likely to improve our understanding of the natural world we live in.
The more we know about animals, the more we can push the frontiers of our knowledge in new and exciting directions for the sake of both humans and animals.
In addition to that, there is some evidence that zoos can contribute to raise people\u2019s awareness on environmental issue.
Parks were animals are hold in captivity are often considered the only bridge between people who live in urban settings and nature itself.
For example, planning a trip on zoos or spending a day in a natural habitat, though artificially recreated, seems to generate a great deal of interest in environmental issues, such as the importance of biodiversity, the risk of loss habitat, the need to respect the ecological balance.
Consequently, with an environmental catastrophe at hand, there is every likelihood that zoos will be playing a role model in conservation efforts over the next years.
To conclude, most animal lovers would agree that zoos are detrimental to animal welfare.
However, increasing numbers of people, myself included, take the view that allowing animals to live and bred in a secure and protect environment will bring about benefits for humanity.
