Many people hold the view that high school students should engage in mandatory volunteerism as part of their academic curriculum.
While it is undoubtedly true that compulsory community service may risk to interfere with students\u2019 homework and home obligations, the opportunities for social activism, personal growth and career development are well-documented.
Therefore, it is evident that students are likely to benefit from engaging in high school compulsory volunteering.
As far as social engagement is concerned, mandatory volunteerism appears to play a key role in nurturing a sense of civic responsibility and good citizenship in young people.
By supporting vulnerable people in the neighbourhood or helping local organisations raise awareness on environmental issues, youngsters can experience the emotional fulfilment of being part of the community.
Consequently, civic engagement will prompt students to become aware of the world around them, foster their understanding of problems and encourage them to be part of the solutions.
A further argument in support of compulsory community service is the personal growth that it sets in motion.
Hands-on experiences in working within difficult contexts and in dealing with people from all walks of life are likely to build youngsters\u2019 character and boost their confidence.
In addition to that, students are bound to learn new skills which will be come in good stead in their professional career: Ability to collaborate with people with diverse backgrounds, effective communication, leadership and empathy will surely be considered a competitive edge in the workplace.
Despite the workload that mandated young volunteers can have, there is no doubt that students will benefit a great deal from experiencing volunteerism throughout the period of their high school attendance.
Their involvement in social activities will shape them into civic-minded citizens, ethic-oriented individuals and high-skilled professionals.
