Computers and other high-tech devices have become essential tools in education.
While I agree that this is true, I also believe that teachers will continue to play a crucial role in the classroom.
On the one hand, I agree with those who claim that blended learning is fundamental to the education sector.
First of all, computer-based lessons are considered more engaging than the ones led by teachers.
Next, interactive websites and online videos are more likely to interest students, thus improving their knowledge retention and performances during exams.
Finally, computers are a potentially unlimited source of information for learners.
A good example could be the following: In the past, students could not help but rely on books and printed maps when asked to do a research project related to geography.
Nowadays, software packages like Google Earth enable students to virtually visit any city of the world, even the most remote villages, thus boosting the learning process.
On the other hand, I believe educators will never become obsolete, no matter how far technology might go in the future.
There are two reasons why I think teachers will always be at the centre of the learning experience.
Not only good educators impart their knowledge, but they also nurture children\u2019s passion for learning and help them develop critical thinking.
Another reason why human interaction at school is essential is empathy.
Teachers can read a student\u2019s face, body language and appearance to infer their emotional state.
They can analyse the complex needs and immediate cues communicated by students e connect with pupils through meaningful conversations and heartfelt listening.
Apart from providing children with invaluable emotional support, teachers can also maintain a close relationship with their parents.
In conclusion, I agree that technology is helpful in the classroom.
However, I believe that teachers will continue to thrive because of their inspirational role in youngsters\u2019 lives.
