There has always been a lively debate surrounding the issue of sleeping habits.
On the one hand, some people extol the benefits of sleeping in dark and silent rooms because this environment lulls them to sleep.
On the other hand, there are those who claim that they can sleep through anything, including claps of thunder, or even their partner\u2019s severe snoring.
As I consider myself a deep sleeper, I do not mind dozing off in an environment where there is little light or noise.
However, either dazzling beams of light or piercing noises are likely to keep me awake throughout the night.
There is much to be said for sleeping in an environment where silence and darkness reign.
There is growing scientific evidence that shows that rooms deprived of noise and dark can create a soothing atmosphere, with beneficial effects on physical and mental wellbeing throughout the night time.
For example, when silence descends in a room, or when the light is turned off, the human body starts to produce melatonin, which is the sleep-inducing hormone.
The more melatonin the body produces, the higher are the chances for people to drift off.
Therefore, having too bright an environment when it is time to sleep can disrupt the natural circadian rhythms, thus making people more alert and prevent them from enjoying a refreshing sleep.
This is the main reason why I prefer sleeping in a free-noise and pitch dark environment.
However, as I have always been a deep sleeper, I do not mind dozing off even in case there is moderate light in the bedroom.
