Studying abroad is a choice that attracts thousands of students every year.
While it is true that this experience has many advantages, it also has its drawbacks.
The beneficial effects of studying in another country are undeniable.
As a start, being exposed to a foreign language is of enormous importance in the language acquisition process.
Therefore, students who are eager to learn a second or a third language are likely to make the most of their experiences abroad.
For example, speaking in daily social contexts may allow young adults to learn the language faster, retain words better and speak with a near-native pronunciation.
In addition to language acquisition, spending time away from home may encourage students to familiarise themselves with different cultures, thus improving their cultural understanding.
For instance, getting to grips with new rules and social norms or engaging with a new culture can turn out to be invaluable tools to see the world through different lenses.
What is more, whichever language students are going to learn, studying abroad will provide them with the opportunity to meet and interact with people from all walks of life.
However, studying abroad is not always associated with positive effects.
First, staying away from home for a certain amount of time can be ridiculously expensive.
Many students cannot simply afford to pay rent or university fees in the first place.
For those who organise the trip on a shoestring, there\u2019s every likelihood that they will come back home frustrated by all the hurdles they had to overcome along the path.
Next, living in a place where the nearest and dearest are far away can be extremely difficult.
The odds are students will feel pangs of nostalgia, with homesickness having its toll on their mental wellbeing.
Cultural shock is another aspect to take into consideration when it comes to the downsides of studying in a host country.
Different countries mean different cultures and social norms.
Adapting to a new culture may cause some physical symptoms such as insomnia, headache and loss of appetite, which are bound to contribute to making the experience disappointing.
There is no denying that studying abroad can be an immense asset for students, especially in the language learning process.
However, this experience can inevitably put students off due to high cost, loneliness and culture shock.
Playing video games has never been so popular among youngsters.
To a certain extent, I agree that this leisure activity may trigger health diseases and deprive young people of social relationships.
However, I also believe that moderate playing can help teenagers enhance their cognitive development and build problem-solving skills.
There are several reasons why playing too much video games may put teenagers\u2019 health in danger and deplete their ability to bond with their peers.
First, spending hours glued to the Tv or computer screen may encourage them to live a sedentary life, thus increasing the risk of developing weight-related diseases such as diabetes or heart problems in the long run.
In addition to health problems, social relationships are also at stake if playing games becomes an addition.
There is no denying that spending too much time engrossed in gaming activities can lead to social isolation, whose inevitable outcomes are likely to be dysfunctional behaviours or poor mental wellbeing.
However, being exposed to video games for a limited amount of time may have a lot of positive influence on young people.
If used with common sense, gaming consoles can help youngsters enhance their cognitive development and build problem-solving skills that may come in handy as they grow up.
For instance, virtual challenges may train young people to make snap decisions to respond to an unexpected threat, which is a vital skill both in virtual and real-life environments.
Online games may also enhance attention, vigilance and concentration.
Mental flexibility is also improved because teenagers and young adults learn how to engage in multiple tasks simultaneously.
There is no doubt that young people are increasingly addicted to video games.
While devoting a great deal of time to this activity may have devastating effects on youngsters\u2019 health and social life, I also think that moderate playing is likely to benefit their cognitive development.
