Obesity in the young is one of the most pressing issues of many developed countries.
To a certain extent, I agree that a sedentary lifestyle, compounded by poor dietary habits, may be detrimental to youngsters\u2019 health.
However, I do not agree that school children and university students should be forced to do sports activities at least three times per week.
Physical activity is undeniably an important way to make youngsters less vulnerable to weight-related health conditions.
However, constantly absorbed by social media platforms and glued to TV screens, children are increasingly spending their free time engaged in virtual gatherings and online gaming platforms, thus drastically reducing the time spent in sports activities with their peers.
This shift towards online playtime, which involves little or almost no exercise, is believed to have major repercussions on youngsters\u2019 health.
As children are becoming more and more obese, weight-related illnesses are on the rise at an alarming pace.
Cardiovascular diseases and chronic health conditions, such as heart attack, stroke and type 2 diabetes, are increasingly affecting the young, thus putting a lot of pressure on national health systems of the developed nations.
However, I do not agree that youngsters should be pressured in sports or team activities on a weekly basis.
First, pushing children to do something beyond their will may end up to be counterproductive.
Sports should be fun, not forced.
And when the reverse is true, youngsters are likely to experience a further drop in motivation which can result in a complete lack of exercise.
Next, forced participation can prevent children from enjoying the activity, both decreasing their desire to succeed and increasing the risk of injuries.
These negative connotations may also cause children to miss out on the importance of physical wellbeing and the benefits associated with sports participation.
On the contrary, students should be encouraged by parents and teachers to stay physically active by embracing activities that can combine fun, entertainment and a flexible amount of exercise.
Finally, pushing children into playing sports at least three times a week can have a negative impact on school achievements.
Being more involved in team sports means that children have less time to focus on their homework but also less energy to devote to academic subjects.
Therefore, I think that a balanced relationship between sports activities and school duties will be more beneficial to children\u2019s physical and mental wellbeing.
