Dear Chris, How are things with you?
Are you enjoying your whirlwind visit to Italy?
I guess you are soaking up the sunny atmosphere and indulging yourself with Italian-style slap-up meals!
So much for you sticking to your diet!
Anyway, first things first.
I am writing to make you aware of some arrangements I have just made ahead of our trip to the Science and Technology museum in Milan, which is scheduled for next Saturday.
As you may already know, Milan is about 50 kilometres away from Bellano, which is the tiny village where my family and I live.
Even though driving is probably the most convenient way to get to Milan, I fear that this option will not be available.
Unfortunately, our family car broke down on a busy road yesterday and we had to call a tow-truck to take it to a local garage to get it repaired.
Therefore, I guess the vehicle will not be roadworthy in the near future.
With driving no longer an option, my siblings and I have decided to go for a train journey.
I already bought your ticket, so you won\u2019t have to worry about queuing at the ticket office the morning of our trip.
Once we get to Milan, we will head to the Science Museum by metro.
Don\u2019t worry, it won\u2019t be a long ride.
The museum headquarters is on the same line of the train station, so the second leg of the journey is going to take just eight minutes, more or less.
The Science Museum we are going to visit is one of the largest scientific and technological museums in Italy.
Visitors can learn about past scientific discoveries through interactive learning and by experimenting with materials and mechanical elements.
In particular, the exhibition we are visiting next Saturday is all about Artificial Intelligence because it displays a collection of portraits made by the world\u2019s first robot artist.
Though futuristic this exhibition may seem, it aims to prompt a large-scale debate about the rapid rise of AI technology and to analyse the relationship between humans and technology.
What stroke me most is the fact that drawings are made by a robot artist, built by a team of programmers, roboticists, art experts and psychologists over a two-year period.
I am looking forward to immersing myself in this virtual environment because I feel this topic is fully contemporary.
I guess we will have a whale of a time!
As I said above, there is no need for you to buy train or subway tickets.
I have already bought them.
Just to be on the safe side, bring a camera with you.
Mine is pretty unreliable and I will not want to risk going back home without photos of this once-in-a-lifetime exhibition!
See you on Saturday!
John
