Should we introduce a mandatory sports activities to university students and school children?
This might be a difficult question, however, it worth examining.
All the evidence suggests that an inactive lifestyle causes the negative effects on health.
A majority of people older than fifty suffers from some kind of chronical diseases, and most of them are not engaged in regular physical activities.
Only when people get older will they realise the importance of excercises.
In my personal view, exposing young people to more physical activity would be the most effective approach the authority could take to improve people's health status.
Therefore, I would definitely agree with mandating sports activities at least three times per week to all university students and school children.
Some people would argue that forcing young people to do physical activity detracts their freedom.
Other may claim that such mandatory program reduces studying time of children.
To a certain limited extent, there is some truth in these arguments.
However, the real situation is that young people would never lose their freedom, rather, they might find important hint on physical activities which they can carry on throughout their life.
In fact, three times per week would only be six hours out of thirty six hours of whole weekly activity.
Any other academic studies can be achieved in the remaining hours.
I would also like to emphasize on the favorable effect of mandatory program.
Children who already like physical activities will do various sports anyway.
It is the matter of children who opt out physical activities. If they were not forced to do sports, how would they find the fun of such activities?
Widening the range of opportunities in the early stage is essential to education.
To conclude, I would insist that young people should be engaged regularly in sports activities.
It would have more positive impact than negative effect.
