While some people contradicts the idea of lying, others might not aggree to such thought.
In my oppinion, lying should not be considered as a evil enemy but a defence mechanism.
In this essay, I will give a reasons for why do poeple tell a lie and I will carefully explain why lying should not adopt in a long run and what would be the negative effects for habit of lying.
Sometimes we end up in a situation where lying seen as a easy way out for that moment.
For instance, when someone needs an opinion of yours about a dress that she is wearing or a movie that you watched last night and it is easy to find yourself in a position where not giving your honest opinion because you want to impress that person and giving a partial truth or not the whole truth might be rewarded as a sympathy and increased interest of other person.
On the other hand, white lies and lying in general might cause some problems in the long run.
Although, at first not telling the truth might gain you some interest, because the perception of others for you are shaped by your lies, in the you have to find your way out of prodigious numbers of misleading informations that you had been given.
That kind of actions becomes as a habit of lying and you will end up in a frustrating life.
In overall, despite the fact that lying can be usefull, it would be wise to use it mindfully because it can transform and demonstrate itself as a dangereous habit.
This letter has been written by a concerned parent.
The news spread that the town council is planning to abolish the use of mobile phones in public transport, in shops and in restaurants.
Although I was raised in a time before internet and the invention of smart phones I plea for accepting the wind of change.
We cannot turn the clock back.
Technology is changing like the rest of society does.
We can't neither deny the existence of the digital era nor ban the use of mobile phones.
These gadgets have become such an integral part of our daily lives that it is unthinkable to set up rules against them.
They deliver a lot of amenities, such as garanteeing freedom, flexibility and independence.
When I have an accident on the motorway I usually phone my garage in order to get immediate help.
I accomplish many tasks via my mobile phone too, such as booking holidays, and giving in my work shift for the next month.
There are disadvantages of mobile phones.
I believe we have lost a lot of skills we had had in former times.
As we continually use our digial helpers for everything we have become addicts to these gadgets.
Skills, such as map reading has been lost too due to the overuse of GPS, or navigational apps.
Nevertheless, these are minor flaws compared to the positive aspects of mobile phones.
Because of all the above mentioned reasons I rather advocate to stick to the remaining status quo to keep the use of mobile phones legal.
Hi Rebecca, How are things with you?
It\u2019s been ages since we last went out for a meal.
I know you\u2019ve been rushed off your feet lately, but I do hope you can free up some time to join me for dinner next Friday.
I\u2019d love to kick off the weekend spending some quality time with you and catching up with all the latest news.
Plus, you must fill me in on all the juicy gossip about your honeymoon!
To mark the occasion, let me ask you over for dinner.
I\u2019ll be treating you with my favourite dish, which is also a true Italian classic: a comforting bowl of tagliatelle with bolognese sauce.
As well as being family-friendly and easy to make, this recipe is a champion of versatility.
Whether you are rustling up a speedy meal in a busy midweek day or you are cooking to impress your friends, tagliatelle with bolognese sauce is always worthwhile.
What I like of this recipe is the fact that I can always rely on it.
For example, if I am up to my ears in work, I usually go for a classic bolognese sauce.
This means that I put onion, celery and carrots in a large pan, I cook them on high heat for five minutes until they are softened, and then I add the mince.
After stirring the mince with a wooden spoon for five minutes on a high heat, I add the passata, then reduce the heat to medium and let the sauce bubble away for 35/40 minutes.
When the thick rag\u00F9 is ready, I bring a large saucepan of salted water to the boil, then I drop in the pasta and cook it until al dente.
Finally, I tip the pasta onto a plate and top with bolognese sauce.
On the contrary, if I\u2019m not snowed under and I want to do some cheering-up activities, I love experimenting with my bolognese sauce by adding some new ingredients, such as smoked pancetta, dried porcini mushrooms and red wine vinegar.
I\u2019ve recently tried my hand at cooking a veggie version of bolognese sauce, which has come down really well among my husband and my in-laws.
I\u2019d really love you to have a taste of my new culinary success because, as you know, I really value your feedback on my cooking.
You can\u2019t miss out on the opportunity to taste this super healthy, low-calorie and yet vibrant dish!
I am sure it will make your mouth water.
The icing on the cake for tagliatelle with bolognese is the fact that it is good for all the seasons.
Being an evergreen dish, pasta can be eaten both in winter and in summer.
I usually get a real kick out of eating bolognese sauce on chilly Sundays, when the days in winter are short and grey.
However, there\u2019s something to be said for eating tagliatelle with bolognese sauce in spring during our family get-togethers spent in the blossoming patio just outside our kitchen.
I hope to have whetted your appetite!
See you on Friday!
Cheers Giovanna
